cluster_relations.rel_desc: Different butterfly species influence the size, shape, and color characteristics of eggs in the egg stage.

qualifiers.ConditionExpression: egg size, shape, and color vary with species
qualifiers.OtherQualifier: AffectedTraits: egg size, egg shape, egg color

cluster_relations.rel_desc: The butterfly species influences how long the metamorphosis process lasts.

qualifiers.ConditionExpression: anywhere from a few days to several weeks

cluster_relations.rel_desc: The duration of the adult butterfly lifespan depends on the butterfly species.

qualifiers.ConditionExpression: lifespan ranges from a few days to a few weeks

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject taxon causally affects the traits or characteristics of the object entity.
args.justification: This relation captures that butterfly species causally affect egg size, shape, and color characteristics in the egg stage; a generic causal-trait predicate fits best without overfitting to life stage specifics.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject causally affects the duration or length of time associated with the object process or state.
args.justification: The description and qualifiers indicate a causal dependency where butterfly species affects how long metamorphosis lasts, best modeled as influencing the duration of the object process.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the existence, value, or magnitude of the subject property is causally dependent on the object entity or factor.
args.justification: Here the subject (adult butterfly lifespan) is explicitly described as depending on the butterfly species, so a directional dependency predicate from effect to cause is appropriate.

All three relations express that life-history traits (egg traits, metamorphosis duration, adult lifespan) are causally constrained by or dependent on butterfly species; grouping them under a shared class for species–life-history dependencies is coherent.
Each relation encodes a causal or dependency relationship (lifespan, traits, and process duration varying depending on species), which fits the broad CAUSALITY group.
